## Context
Follow-up from 0216 (fast-path tier guards, PR #978, tracker 0213). The
collection-time auto-mark works (verified live: check-fast ~93s → ~24s, no
dcor/heavy test on the fast path). Two non-blocking robustness gaps surfaced in
the /gaze review of #978:

1. **Hook-ordering assumption is unpinned.** The auto-mark relies on
   `pytest_collection_modifyitems` (conftest) running before pytest's core `-m`
   mark-filter. Verified to hold under pytest 9.0.2, but no regression test locks
   it — a future pytest hook-ordering change could silently defeat the auto-mark
   with no test failure. (built-in reviewer, #978)
2. **Module-granularity over-sweeps.** The scanner marks a whole file `slow` when
   its source contains a heavy import, even a lazy one fired by only a few tests.
   Concrete: `tests/test_null_model.py` imports torch only inside two
   CUDA-skip-guarded methods, yet all 37 tests (34 unrelated to torch) leave the
   fast path. Safe direction (they still run in `make check`) and intentional per
   0216, but the scale of lost fast-path coverage is under-quantified. (panel
   reviewer, #978)

## Relevant files
- `tests/conftest.py` — `pytest_collection_modifyitems` auto-mark hook
- `tests/_tier_autoscan.py` — static heavy-import scanner
- `tests/test_fast_path_budget.py` — ratchet + unit tests for the scanner

## Actions
1. Add a `pytester`/`testdir`-based regression test (integration tier) that
   spins a real collection with a synthetic heavy-import module and asserts it is
   deselected under `-m "not slow and not integration and not adherence"` and
   selected under `-m slow` — pinning the hook-ordering behaviour.
2. Quantify the over-sweep: count tests moved off the fast path whose module's
   heavy import is lazy and never fired by that test. Decide whether per-test
   refinement (e.g. only auto-mark tests whose own body/callees reach the import)
   is worth the added fragility, or whether module-granularity is the right
   conservative default (document the decision either way).

## Test
Write first (red): the pytester regression test from action 1 (fails if the hook
ordering ever stops deselecting the synthetic heavy-import test).

## Findings & decision (2026-07-10)

### Action 1 — hook ordering pinned
`tests/test_fast_path_hook_ordering.py` (integration tier) spins a real
collection in a throwaway dir whose conftest mirrors the production auto-mark
(same `file_has_heavy_import`, same `add_marker(slow)` in
`pytest_collection_modifyitems`) and asserts a synthetic heavy-import test is
deselected under the fast-path selector and selected under `-m slow`.
`--collect-only` keeps the synthetic module's lazy import from firing. Teeth
verified by mutation: disabling the `add_marker` call fails the deselection
assertion.

### Action 2 — over-sweep quantified, module granularity kept
Measured over the current suite: 95 test functions (~120 collected items) across
7 heavy-import modules are auto-marked with no explicit marker of their own.
Breakdown by whether per-test refinement could recover fast-path time:
- **Heavy compute (~104 items)** — `test_divergence` (56), `test_null_model`
  (37), `test_embedding_sensitivity` (11): each runs tens of seconds even with
  the heavy import excluded (all timed out >55s). The layer-2 duration ratchet
  would bounce them off the fast path anyway — the auto-mark agrees with it, not
  over-reaches. Recoverable time: none.
- **Top-level import** — `test_pipeline_io` (2): imports matplotlib at module
  top level, so importing the module already pays the tax. Per-test marking
  cannot help.
- **Genuinely light + lazy import (~12 items)** — `test_analytical_null` (~3.3s)
  and `test_zoo_figure_polish` (~2.6s): the only recoverable set, and each still
  retains one matplotlib-touching test.

**Decision: keep module granularity.** Recovering ~12 quick tests in two modules
would require *sound* per-test detection of which tests reach a lazy import
(through fixtures, helpers, transitive calls — not a body scan), a fragile
re-implementation of pytest's machinery whose false negatives would silently
readmit the exact import tax the guard removes. No coverage is lost (every
over-swept test still runs in `make check`), and an over-swept test can be run in
the inner loop directly (`pytest tests/test_foo.py::test_bar`, no `-m` filter).
Decision recorded in `tests/_tier_autoscan.py::file_has_heavy_import` docstring.

## Exit criteria
- [x] Hook-ordering pinned by a regression test.
- [x] Over-sweep quantified; a documented decision on module- vs per-test granularity.
